To convert a single character to its corresponding Unicode code point using the Converter library, you can use the `encode` method with UTF-16 encoding. Here's an example in Java:

```java
import org.apache.commons.text.encoding.UnicodeEncodings;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String character = "A";
        byte[] bytes = Character.toString(character.charAt(0)).getBytes(UnicodeEncodings.UTF_16);
        int unicodeCodePoint = 0;

        for (byte b : bytes) {
            if ((b & 0x80) != 0) {
                unicodeCodePoint |= (0xFF & b) << (8 * (bytes.length - 1 - IndexOf.index(bytes, b)));
            } else {
                unicodeCodePoint += b;
            }
        }

        System.out.println("Unicode code point for character '" + character + "' is: " + Integer.toHexString(unicodeCodePoint));
    }
}
```

This example converts the character 'A' to its Unicode code point and prints it out in hexadecimal format.

