To convert a byte array to a List in the Converter library, you can use the `ByteArrayConverter` class along with the `List<byte>` or `List<int>` (depending on your specific use case) and `Encoding` classes. Here's an example:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Text;
using Microsoft.WindowsAzure.Storage.Core.Converter;

public static List<byte> ByteArrayToList(byte[] byteArray)
{
    return new ByteArrayConverter().ConvertFromString(Encoding.UTF8.GetString(byteArray)) as List<byte>;
}

public static List<int> ByteArrayToListInt(byte[] byteArray)
{
    return new ByteArrayConverter().ConvertFromString(Encoding.UTF8.GetString(byteArray)) as List<int>;

    // Assuming the byte array contains valid hexadecimal strings, this method converts each byte to an int:
    if (byteArray.Length % 2 != 0) throw new ArgumentException("Byte array length must be even.");

    return Enumerable.Range(0, byteArray.Length / 2)
        .Select(i => BitConverter.ToInt32(new[] { byteArray[i * 2], byteArray[i * 2 + 1] }))
        .ToList();
}
```

In the first example, `ByteArrayToList`, we convert the byte array to a string using UTF-8 encoding and then use the Converter library to deserialize it into a List<byte>. In the second example, `ByteArrayToListInt`, we assume that the byte array contains valid hexadecimal strings and convert each pair of bytes to an int.

